This paper proposes a framework for autonomous driving that combines learning- and optimization-based approaches. The focus is on achieving desirable driving quality in a long-term horizon with guaranteed safety and feasibility. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of a neural network for the policy layer, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of optimization-based approaches, which suggests that it may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-categories. Finally, the paper mentions the use of features and trajectories, which suggests that it may also belong to the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category.
